  <h2 id="abstract">Abstract</h2>
  <p>AI safety discourse has a vocabulary problem. Failure modes at the governance layer, the policies, escalation paths, audit systems, and human review processes that wrap AI models, are poorly named, inconsistently described, and not shared across the engineering, legal, policy, and research communities that need to communicate about the same events. This paper introduces the SVRNOS AI Governance Error Taxonomy: a structured classification system for AI platform governance failures organized by numeric codes derived from HTTP protocol error semantics. The taxonomy covers twenty-seven structurally distinct failure modes and success states across five tiers: pre-infrastructure, success states, structural moves, operator errors, and infrastructure failures. Seven codes extend beyond standard HTTP where no existing code maps cleanly to the governance failure. The taxonomy is a signaling layer, not a policy layer, codes describe what failed, they do not define what platforms are required to do. The register is open and extensible. SVRNOS maintains it. This is v0.1.</p>

